{"id":"1507.05199","submitter":"Prasad Subramanian Dr","authors":"Nishtha Sachdeva, Prasad Subramanian, Robin Colaninno, Angelos\n  Vourlidas","title":"CME propagation: Where does solar wind drag take over?","comments":"Accepted, ApJ. Current version matches published version","journal-ref":"ApJ, 2015, 809, 158","doi":"10.1088/0004-637X/809/2/158","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR physics.plasm-ph physics.space-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the Sun-Earth dynamics of a set of eight well observed solar\ncoronal mass ejections (CMEs) using data from the STEREO spacecraft. We seek to\nquantify the extent to which momentum coupling between these CMEs and the\nambient solar wind (i.e., the aerodynamic drag) influences their dynamics. To\nthis end, we use results from a 3D flux rope model fit to the CME data. We find\nthat solar wind aerodynamic drag adequately accounts for the dynamics of the\nfastest CME in our sample. For the relatively slower CMEs, we find that\ndrag-based models initiated below heliocentric distances ranging from 15 to 50\n$R_{\\odot}$ cannot account for the observed CME trajectories. This is at\nvariance with the general perception that the dynamics of slow CMEs are\ninfluenced primarily by solar wind drag from a few $R_{\\odot}$ onwards. Several\nslow CMEs propagate at roughly constant speeds above 15--50 $R_{\\odot}$.\nDrag-based models initiated above these heights therefore require negligible\naerodynamic drag to explain their observed trajectories.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 18 Jul 2015 16:05:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 21 Aug 2015 06:29:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-08-24"}
